{
  "What is the Green Revolution?": "",
  "The development and adoption of high-yield crop varieties, irrigation, and synthetic fertilizers that dramatically increased food production": "",
  "A revolution led by environmentalists against industrial farming": "",
  "The shift from agriculture to manufacturing in developing countries": "",
  "A political movement promoting organic farming": "",
  "The Green Revolution, beginning in the 1960s, involved the development of high-yield crop varieties, expanded irrigation, and increased use of synthetic fertilizers and pesticides, dramatically boosting food production in developing nations.": "",
  "Which agricultural practice involves growing a single crop over a large area?": "",
  "Monoculture": "",
  "Polyculture": "",
  "Crop rotation": "",
  "Agroforestry": "",
  "Monoculture is the agricultural practice of growing a single crop species over a large area, which maximizes efficiency and yields but increases vulnerability to pests and disease and depletes specific soil nutrients.": "",
  "What is the primary environmental concern with heavy pesticide use in agriculture?": "",
  "Pesticides cause crops to grow too quickly": "",
  "Pesticides can harm non-target organisms, contaminate water, and accumulate in food chains": "",
  "Pesticides make food taste different": "",
  "Pesticides only affect the specific pest they target": "",
  "Pesticides can kill beneficial insects like pollinators, contaminate groundwater and surface water through runoff, and bioaccumulate through food chains, harming wildlife and potentially human health.": "",
  "Which farming method integrates trees with crops or livestock on the same land?": "",
  "Industrial feedlot operation": "",
  "Monoculture farming": "",
  "Slash-and-burn agriculture": "",
  "Agroforestry deliberately combines trees and shrubs with crops and/or livestock on the same land, creating diversified and sustainable systems that can improve soil health, increase biodiversity, and provide multiple products.": "",
  "What is a major environmental impact of concentrated animal feeding operations (CAFOs)?": "",
  "They require very little water": "",
  "They reduce greenhouse gas emissions": "",
  "They produce large amounts of animal waste that can pollute water and air": "",
  "They increase local biodiversity": "",
  "CAFOs concentrate thousands of animals in confined spaces, generating enormous amounts of waste that can contaminate local waterways with nutrients and pathogens, emit greenhouse gases like methane, and create air quality problems.": "",
  "What is the primary benefit of integrated pest management (IPM)?": "",
  "It eliminates all pests permanently": "",
  "It reduces pesticide use by combining biological, cultural, and chemical control methods": "",
  "It only uses genetically modified crops": "",
  "It requires more pesticides than conventional methods": "",
  "IPM is a sustainable approach that combines multiple pest control strategies including biological controls, habitat manipulation, resistant crop varieties, and targeted chemical use to manage pests with minimal environmental impact.": "",
  "How does excessive nitrogen fertilizer use affect nearby aquatic ecosystems?": "",
  "It cools water temperatures to benefit aquatic life": "",
  "It has no effect on aquatic systems": "",
  "It causes eutrophication, leading to algal blooms and oxygen depletion": "",
  "It improves fish habitat by adding nutrients": "",
  "Excess nitrogen from fertilizer runoff enters waterways and stimulates rapid algal growth (eutrophication); when algae die and decompose, bacteria consume dissolved oxygen, creating hypoxic dead zones that can kill fish and other aquatic organisms.": "",
  "What is genetic engineering in agriculture primarily used for?": "",
  "To develop crop varieties with desired traits such as pest resistance or increased yields": "",
  "To create crops that change color for aesthetic purposes": "",
  "To eliminate the need for sunlight in farming": "",
  "To make crops require more water": "",
  "Genetic engineering in agriculture involves modifying crop DNA to introduce desirable traits such as pest resistance, herbicide tolerance, drought tolerance, or improved nutritional content, aiming to increase productivity and reduce losses.": "",
  "Which of the following is a sustainable agricultural practice?": "",
  "Applying maximum amounts of pesticide to prevent any pest damage": "",
  "Clearing old-growth forest for new farmland each year": "",
  "Using drip irrigation to minimize water waste": "",
  "Plowing steep hillsides without terracing": "",
  "Drip irrigation delivers water directly to plant roots through a network of tubes, minimizing evaporation and runoff, reducing water usage by up to 60% compared to flood irrigation while maintaining or improving crop yields.": "",
  "What is the main disadvantage of slash-and-burn agriculture?": "",
  "It requires expensive machinery, despite what intuition might initially suggest": "",
  "It leads to deforestation and soil degradation when practiced on large scales or without adequate fallow periods": "",
  "It produces too much food, despite what intuition might initially suggest": "",
  "It can only be practiced in cold climates when viewed through a simplified analytical lens": "",
  "Slash-and-burn agriculture involves clearing and burning forest to create farmland; while sustainable on small scales with long fallow periods, it causes severe deforestation, habitat loss, and soil degradation when practiced intensively or without sufficient recovery time.": "",
  "What is 'organic farming'?": "",
  "A type of farming practiced only in laboratories": "",
  "Farming that uses any method to maximize production regardless of chemicals used": "",
  "An agricultural system that avoids synthetic pesticides and fertilizers, relying on natural processes and inputs": "",
  "Farming that uses only genetically modified organisms": "",
  "Organic farming is an agricultural system that relies on natural inputs like compost, biological pest control, and crop rotation rather than synthetic pesticides and fertilizers, aiming to maintain ecological balance and soil health.": "",
  "What does 'subsistence agriculture' mean?": "",
  "Growing crops in greenhouses year-round": "",
  "Large-scale commercial farming for export": "",
  "Farming that relies entirely on government subsidies": "",
  "Farming primarily to feed the farmer's family, with little or no surplus for sale": "",
  "Subsistence agriculture is a farming system in which farmers grow food primarily to feed themselves and their families, producing little or no surplus for trade; it is still practiced by billions of people in developing countries.": "",
  "What does 'biological pest control' mean?": "",
  "Genetically modifying pests so they cannot reproduce": "",
  "Using natural predators, parasites, or pathogens to control pest populations": "",
  "Using chemical pesticides derived from biological sources": "",
  "Biologically engineering new pesticides in a laboratory": "",
  "Biological pest control uses natural enemies of pests, including predators (like ladybugs), parasitoids (like parasitic wasps), and pathogens (like Bt bacteria), to reduce pest populations as an alternative to chemical pesticides.": "",
  "What does 'waterlogging' refer to in agriculture?": "",
  "Using logs to dam streams for irrigation": "",
  "The saturation of soil with water to the point that plant roots cannot get adequate oxygen": "",
  "The natural flooding of wetland areas": "",
  "The recording of water usage data in a logbook": "",
  "Waterlogging occurs when the soil becomes saturated with water, often due to poor drainage or over-irrigation, filling all pore spaces and depriving plant roots of oxygen, which stunts growth or kills crops.": "",
  "What is meant by 'food security'?": "",
  "The condition in which all people have reliable access to sufficient, safe, and nutritious food": "",
  "The freshness of food in grocery stores": "",
  "The physical security of food storage facilities": "",
  "The ability of a country to export food to other nations": "",
  "Food security exists when all people at all times have physical, social, and economic access to sufficient, safe, and nutritious food to meet their dietary needs and food preferences for an active and healthy life.": "",
  "What does 'pesticide resistance' mean?": "",
  "The chemical stability of pesticides in storage": "",
  "The evolutionary adaptation of pest populations to survive exposure to pesticides": "",
  "Farmers resisting the use of pesticides on their crops": "",
  "Crops that are naturally resistant to pesticide damage": "",
  "Pesticide resistance is the genetic adaptation of pest populations through natural selection; individuals with traits that allow survival after pesticide exposure reproduce, passing resistance to offspring, eventually making the pesticide ineffective against the pest.": "",
  "What is 'aquaculture'?": "",
  "The natural growth of organisms in rivers and lakes": "",
  "A system for purifying water for agriculture": "",
  "The farming of aquatic organisms such as fish, shellfish, and algae in controlled environments": "",
  "The scientific study of water quality": "",
  "Aquaculture is the controlled cultivation of aquatic organisms including fish, crustaceans, mollusks, and aquatic plants for food production, and it is the fastest-growing sector of food production globally.": "",
  "What does the term 'genetically modified organism (GMO)' mean?": "",
  "An organism that has naturally mutated in the wild": "",
  "An organism whose genetic material has been altered using genetic engineering techniques": "",
  "An organism that has been selectively bred over many generations": "",
  "An organism that has been exposed to radiation": "",
  "A GMO is an organism whose DNA has been directly modified using biotechnology techniques such as gene insertion or deletion to introduce specific desired traits that would not occur naturally through conventional breeding.": "",
  "What is the definition of 'topsoil loss'?": "",
  "The removal of the fertile upper layer of soil through erosion or degradation": "",
  "The conversion of topsoil into bedrock": "",
  "The natural deepening of soil over time": "",
  "The addition of new soil to the land surface": "",
  "Topsoil loss refers to the removal of the fertile A horizon through erosion by wind or water, often accelerated by poor agricultural practices; since topsoil can take centuries to form, its rapid loss severely threatens agricultural productivity.": "",
  "What does 'polyculture' mean?": "",
  "Farming in multiple countries simultaneously": "",
  "Farming that uses only machines and no manual labor": "",
  "Growing a single crop on the same land year after year": "",
  "Growing multiple crop species together on the same land": "",
  "Polyculture is the agricultural practice of growing two or more crop species in the same space, mimicking natural ecosystems; it increases biodiversity, reduces pest problems, improves soil health, and can provide more stable yields than monoculture.": "",
  "A large-scale corn farmer in Iowa applies 200 kg of nitrogen fertilizer per hectare each year. Water quality monitoring downstream reveals elevated nitrate levels in the local river, and the Gulf of Mexico experiences its annual hypoxic dead zone. How are the farmer's practices connected to the dead zone over 1,500 km away?": "",
  "The fertilizer evaporates and is carried to the Gulf by wind": "",
  "Excess nitrogen fertilizer runs off into the Mississippi River watershed and flows to the Gulf, causing eutrophication and oxygen depletion": "",
  "The dead zone is caused solely by ocean temperature changes": "",
  "There is no connection between Iowa farming and the Gulf of Mexico": "",
  "Nitrogen fertilizer not absorbed by crops enters waterways through runoff and subsurface flow, traveling through the Mississippi River watershed to the Gulf of Mexico, where it fuels massive algal blooms whose decomposition depletes oxygen, creating one of the world's largest hypoxic dead zones.": "",
  "A developing nation is considering adopting Green Revolution technologies to increase food production. Critics warn of potential negative consequences. Which of the following is a legitimate concern about implementing Green Revolution practices?": "",
  "Green Revolution crops cannot grow in tropical climates": "",
  "The technology has been proven to be completely ineffective at increasing yields": "",
  "High-yield varieties always produce less food than traditional varieties": "",
  "Dependence on expensive inputs like synthetic fertilizers and irrigation can increase debt and environmental degradation": "",
  "While Green Revolution technologies increase yields, they require expensive inputs (seeds, fertilizers, pesticides, irrigation) that can trap small farmers in debt, deplete groundwater, degrade soil, and reduce crop genetic diversity, creating environmental and economic vulnerabilities.": "",
  "A farmer notices that after 10 years of applying the same insecticide to cotton fields, the bollworm pest is no longer controlled by the chemical. The farmer must now use higher doses or switch to a stronger insecticide. What biological process explains this phenomenon?": "",
  "Natural selection has favored bollworms with genetic resistance to the insecticide": "",
  "The bollworms have learned to avoid the chemical": "",
  "The insecticide has expired and lost its potency": "",
  "Climate change has made the insecticide chemically unstable": "",
  "Repeated application of the same insecticide exerts strong selective pressure; individuals with genetic mutations conferring resistance survive and reproduce, passing resistance genes to their offspring, eventually resulting in a population dominated by resistant individuals.": "",
  "A community in Southeast Asia practices traditional rice paddy farming where ducks are released into the paddies to eat insects and weeds, and fish are raised in the flooded fields alongside the rice. This contrasts with a neighboring industrial rice farm that uses synthetic pesticides and herbicides. What advantages does the traditional system offer?": "",
  "It requires more expensive inputs than industrial farming": "",
  "It produces more rice per hectare than industrial farming": "",
  "It eliminates the need for water in rice production": "",
  "It provides multiple food products, reduces chemical inputs, and maintains ecosystem health through integrated pest management": "",
  "This traditional integrated farming system produces rice, duck meat, eggs, and fish while using ducks and fish as biological pest and weed control, reducing the need for synthetic chemicals, maintaining biodiversity, and recycling nutrients within the system.": "",
  "An environmental scientist compares the water usage of two farms: Farm A uses flood irrigation, while Farm B uses drip irrigation for the same crop. Farm B uses 40% less water and has higher yields. What explains Farm B's better water efficiency?": "",
  "Farm B's soil naturally holds more water": "",
  "Drip irrigation works by collecting atmospheric moisture": "",
  "Drip irrigation delivers water directly to plant roots, minimizing evaporation, runoff, and deep percolation losses": "",
  "Drip irrigation floods the soil more effectively": "",
  "Drip irrigation delivers water slowly and directly to the root zone through a network of pipes and emitters, drastically reducing water lost to evaporation from wet soil surfaces, surface runoff, and deep percolation beyond the root zone compared to flood irrigation.": "",
  "A cattle rancher in Brazil clears 500 hectares of Amazon rainforest for pastureland. After 5-8 years, the soil fertility declines so much that the pasture can no longer support cattle, and the rancher considers clearing more forest. What explains this cycle of degradation?": "",
  "Tropical rainforest soils are nutrient-poor; nutrients were stored in the biomass, and once the forest is removed, rapid leaching depletes the thin fertile layer": "",
  "The cattle are eating too much grass, as most introductory frameworks would predict when analyzing soil dynamics": "",
  "The rainfall increases after deforestation, flooding the pastures, despite what intuition might initially suggest": "",
  "Brazil's climate is too cold for cattle ranching within the broader context of soil analysis": "",
  "Tropical rainforest ecosystems store most nutrients in living biomass rather than soil; when the forest is cleared and burned, the nutrient flush from ash is quickly depleted by heavy tropical rains that leach nutrients from the exposed soil, rendering it infertile within years.": "",
  "A food policy analyst argues that reducing meat consumption in wealthy countries could significantly decrease agriculture's environmental footprint. What is the scientific basis for this argument?": "",
  "Meat consumption only affects local environments, not global systems": "",
  "Meat production has no environmental impact compared to crop production": "",
  "Livestock require large amounts of feed crops, water, and land, and produce significant greenhouse gas emissions per calorie of food produced": "",
  "Vegetable farming uses more water than livestock farming": "",
  "Producing animal protein requires far more resources than plant protein: it takes roughly 6-10 kg of grain to produce 1 kg of beef, and livestock account for approximately 14.5% of global greenhouse gas emissions while using about 70% of agricultural land.": "",
  "An organic farmer uses crop rotation with nitrogen-fixing legumes, applies composted manure, and releases ladybugs to control aphids. A neighboring conventional farmer argues that organic methods cannot feed the world. What is the strongest counterargument the organic farmer could make?": "",
  "Organic farming requires no knowledge or skill to practice": "",
  "Conventional farming has no advantages over organic farming": "",
  "Organic farming always produces higher yields than conventional farming": "",
  "Organic methods build long-term soil health and resilience, reduce external input costs, and can achieve competitive yields when well-managed while avoiding environmental degradation": "",
  "While organic farming may have slightly lower yields for some crops, it builds long-term soil health, reduces dependence on expensive synthetic inputs, maintains biodiversity, and avoids the environmental degradation that threatens the long-term sustainability of conventional agriculture.": "",
  "A region experiences a severe drought, and a farmer growing only one variety of wheat loses the entire crop. A neighboring farmer growing five different heritage wheat varieties loses some crops but harvests enough to survive. What agricultural concept does this scenario illustrate?": "",
  "The superiority of modern crop varieties over heritage varieties": "",
  "The importance of genetic diversity and crop variety for resilience to environmental stress": "",
  "The advantage of monoculture for maximizing yields": "",
  "The irrelevance of crop choice in drought conditions": "",
  "Genetic diversity provides insurance against crop failure; different varieties have different tolerances to environmental stresses, so growing multiple varieties reduces the risk of total loss and demonstrates why maintaining agricultural biodiversity is critical for food security.": "",
  "A government subsidizes the construction of a massive dam and irrigation system to convert arid land into productive farmland. Initially, crop yields are excellent. After 15 years, however, white salt deposits cover much of the soil surface, and yields have plummeted. What mistake did the planners fail to anticipate?": "",
  "The irrigation system delivered too little water to the crops": "",
  "The dam prevented fish migration, affecting the food supply": "",
  "In arid climates, irrigation water evaporates and leaves dissolved salts behind, causing progressive salinization that degrades soil": "",
  "Crops cannot grow on land that was previously arid": "",
  "In arid regions, irrigation water contains dissolved salts; as water evaporates from the soil surface, these salts accumulate over time (salinization), eventually reaching concentrations toxic to crops; proper drainage systems are essential but often overlooked in irrigation planning.": ""
